For UI-oriented applications (especially mobile ones) it is very common to skip rendering if nothing has been changed. It is possible to add check function to Stage object and test this condition as prerequest in `Starling:render()` (together with `contextValid` check). Naive implementation (just copy-paste from `DOC:render`):

```
public function isNeedsRender(painter:Painter):Boolean
{
    var numChildren:int = _children.length;
    var frameID:uint = painter.frameID;
    var selfOrParentChanged:Boolean = _lastParentOrSelfChangeFrameID == frameID;
    for (var i:int=0; i<numChildren; ++i)
    {
        var child:DisplayObject = _children[i];

        if (child._hasVisibleArea)
        {
            if (selfOrParentChanged)
                child._lastParentOrSelfChangeFrameID = frameID;

            if (child._lastParentOrSelfChangeFrameID != frameID &&
                    child._lastChildChangeFrameID != frameID &&
                    child._tokenFrameID == frameID - 1)
            {
                // cache
            }
            else
            {
                return true;
            }
        }
    }
    return false;
}
```

Could you change `QuadBatch.dispose()` this way:

``` as3
public override function dispose():void
{
    Starling.current.stage3D.removeEventListener(Event.CONTEXT3D_CREATE, onContextCreated);
    destroyBuffers();

    if(mVertexData != null) {
        mVertexData.numVertices = 0;
        mVertexData = null;
    }

    if(mIndexData != null) {
        mIndexData.length = 0;
        mIndexData = null;
    }

    mNumQuads = 0;

    if (mTexture && mOwnsTexture)
        mTexture.dispose();

    super.dispose();
}
```

It releases VertexData and IndexData (which consume the most of the memory used by QuadBatches) even if QuadBatch itself is not released (e.g. due to a bug in Adobe's GC, like this one: http://forum.starling-framework.org/topic/bug-things-not-getting-disposed). It has no negative impact or performance or anything.

Hi, Daniel. I think i found a bug in the mask implementation in Starling 2.0.

```
var image:Image = new Image(Texture.fromEmbeddedAsset(EMBEDDED_TEXTURE));
image.mask = new Quad(200, 200);
//image.mask.rotation = 0.001;
image.x = 100;
image.y = 100;
this.addChild(image);
```

If you uncomment the line that sets the rotation of the mask, the result is expected to look nearly the same. Instead, you can see that the scissor rectangle masking starts at the stage's origin, while the stencil buffer masking starts at image's origin.

